 {"id":"franken_networkx-nxsubview","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] nx.subgraph_view / induced_subgraph / restricted_view fail on fnx graphs","description":"nx's subgraph_view helper does newG = G.__class__.__new__(G.__class__); newG._node = FilterAtlas(...); newG._adj = FilterAdjacency(...); newG.graph = G.graph. fnx's _node/_adj/_succ/_pred are read-only property descriptors, so the assignment raises 'AttributeError: property has no setter'. Making them settable exposes a deeper problem: fnx.Graph.edges / .nodes / .degree go direct to the Rust store and ignore the stashed overrides, yielding silently-empty views. fnx.subgraph / fnx.subgraph_view / fnx.restricted_view work because they have custom implementations. nx.subgraph delegates to G.subgraph and also works. But nx.induced_subgraph and nx.restricted_view go through nx.subgraph_view unconditionally. Proper fix is a larger refactor: either (a) route edges/nodes/adj through the override when present on the instance, or (b) monkey-patch nx.subgraph_view to dispatch to fnx when passed a fnx graph. Queued — needs design.","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T09:47:17.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T09:47:17.000000000Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-rrgval","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] random_regular_graph leaks Rust FailClosed ValueError on invalid args","description":"fnx.random_regular_graph(d, n) with invalid (d, n) like (0, 0) or (3, 0) raised 'ValueError(\"FailClosed { operation: \"random_regular_graph\", reason: ... }\")' instead of nx's NetworkXError('the 0 <= d < n inequality must be satisfied'). The nx-shaped validation lived AFTER the 'if create_using is None: return _rust_random_regular_graph(...)' branch, so the no-create_using call path (the default) skipped all validation and leaked the Rust FailClosed surface. Fixed in Round 14 Cycle 1 by moving both validations (0 <= d < n and n*d even) above the Rust branch.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","close_reason":"Validation moved above Rust branch; errors now raise NetworkXError with nx wording","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-badiacritic","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] Barabási–Albert error messages used ASCII instead of nx Unicode","description":"nx uses 'Barabási–Albert' (with diacritics on the second 'a' and an en-dash) in error messages for barabasi_albert_graph and dual_barabasi_albert_graph. fnx used ASCII 'Barabasi-Albert' for both, breaking regex-matched pytest.raises(..., match=...) patterns and user documentation snippets. Fixed to mirror nx character-for-character. Note: nx DOES use ASCII 'Barabasi-Albert' for extended_barabasi_albert_graph, so that one stays ASCII.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","close_reason":"Updated to match nx exactly (Unicode for ba/dual, ASCII for extended)","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
-{"id":"franken_networkx-nxexcbases","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] _fnx exception hierarchy not compatible with nx exception hierarchy","description":"Every _fnx.*Error class is defined with pyo3::create_exception! rooted at PyException — NOT at the corresponding nx.*Error. So 'isinstance(fnx_err, nx.NetworkXError)' is False for every raised fnx exception. User code that does 'except nx.NetworkXError' (a reasonable drop-in expectation) silently misses fnx errors. Checked: NetworkXError, NetworkXNotImplemented, NetworkXPointlessConcept, NodeNotFound, NetworkXUnfeasible, NetworkXNoPath, NetworkXNoCycle, NetworkXUnbounded, NotATree, HasACycle, PowerIterationFailedConvergence, NetworkXAlgorithmError — all fail issubclass. Rebasing in Python (._fnx.NetworkXError.__bases__ = (nx.NetworkXError,)) fails with 'object layout differs from Exception'. Proper fix is Rust-side: define exceptions as subclasses of the networkx equivalents by looking up the nx class at Rust module init (via PyModule::import) and constructing each exception type manually (PyErr_NewException with a runtime base) instead of the compile-time create_exception! macro. Big change — Rust-side, 12 exception types. Queued.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:01:32.050817957Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-nxexcbases","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] _fnx exception hierarchy not compatible with nx exception hierarchy","description":"Every _fnx.*Error class is defined with pyo3::create_exception! rooted at PyException — NOT at the corresponding nx.*Error. So 'isinstance(fnx_err, nx.NetworkXError)' is False for every raised fnx exception. User code that does 'except nx.NetworkXError' (a reasonable drop-in expectation) silently misses fnx errors. Checked: NetworkXError, NetworkXNotImplemented, NetworkXPointlessConcept, NodeNotFound, NetworkXUnfeasible, NetworkXNoPath, NetworkXNoCycle, NetworkXUnbounded, NotATree, HasACycle, PowerIterationFailedConvergence, NetworkXAlgorithmError — all fail issubclass. Rebasing in Python (._fnx.NetworkXError.__bases__ = (nx.NetworkXError,)) fails with 'object layout differs from Exception'. Proper fix is Rust-side: define exceptions as subclasses of the networkx equivalents by looking up the nx class at Rust module init (via PyModule::import) and constructing each exception type manually (PyErr_NewException with a runtime base) instead of the compile-time create_exception! macro. Big change — Rust-side, 12 exception types. Queued.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T09:53:55.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:11:46.625811580Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:11:46.625811580Z","close_reason":"Completed native exception exports use upstream NetworkX classes","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-parityrec","title":"REVIEW: [CRITICAL] parity-fallback infinite recursion when backend_priority set","description":"When a user configures 'nx.config.backend_priority = [\"franken_networkx\"]' for transparent accel, and calls an algorithm where fnx can't honour some argument (e.g. 'flow_func=' on max-flow, 'method=' on average_shortest_path_length), fnx delegates via _call_networkx_for_parity which calls 'getattr(nx, name)(_networkx_graph_for_parity(G), *args, **kwargs)'. That re-enters nx's dispatcher which, seeing backend_priority, routes RIGHT BACK INTO the same fnx wrapper -> infinite recursion until Python's default recursion limit. User never sees a result. Fix: set 'backend=\"networkx\"' in kwargs before the nx call in both _call_networkx_for_parity and _call_networkx_submodule_for_parity so nx's _dispatchable honours the explicit override and skips dispatch. Regression test tests/python/test_backend_dispatch_recursion_parity.py covers max-flow with flow_func, aspl with method, and the default (no-fallback) path.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:00:01.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:00:01.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:00:01.000000000Z","close_reason":"kwargs.setdefault('backend', 'networkx') in both parity helpers","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-diffnodes","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] difference / symmetric_difference skipped nx's equal-node-set precondition","description":"nx.difference(G, H) and nx.symmetric_difference(G, H) both raise NetworkXError('Node sets of graphs not equal') when G.nodes != H.nodes. fnx's implementations went straight to the Rust edge-set operation without checking, silently diverging on any mismatched input. Fixed by adding the precondition at the top of each wrapper. Regression test in tests/python/test_operators_conformance.py exercises the raise + happy path.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:08:38.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:08:38.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:08:38.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added 'if set(G.nodes()) != set(H.nodes()): raise NetworkXError' guards","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-gnrempty","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] gnc_graph(0) / gnr_graph(0) returned empty graph instead of nx's single seed node","description":"nx.gnc_graph(0, seed=42) and nx.gnr_graph(0, 0.5, seed=42) both return a 1-node DiGraph (node 0 is the initial seed of the growth loop). fnx's default path went straight to the Rust _fnx.gnc_graph/_fnx.gnr_graph which returned the empty graph for n=0. The existing create_using branch already did the right thing, but the fast path bypassed it. Fixed by hoisting the n==0 special-case above the Rust dispatch in both wrappers.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:16:31.000000000Z","close_reason":"Hoisted n==0 branch above the Rust fast-path in both gnc_graph and gnr_graph","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}

